answers.body_markdown:
ArrayList is a generic type.

So it can&#39;t work with primitive type.

It work with object type and use array object for internal implementation.

    Object elements[]= new Object[size];

For example custom list:

    public class MyList{
        private static final int DEFAULT_CAPACITY = 10;
        private Object elements[];
    
        public MyList() {
            elements = new Object[DEFAULT_CAPACITY];
        }
    }

ArrayList always requires object to store it in the list, It uses generics to create a list for specific type. For Example:

    ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt; intList = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
This creates a arraylist for Integer type, here Integer is a wrapper class for the primitive data type int, we can&#39;t create arraylist of primitive type, we need to use a wrapper class. If you don&#39;t use generics then:

    ArrayList&lt;&gt; intList = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

by default, it&#39;s get created for the Object class, which is super class of all the classes including the wrapper one.
Now:

    ArrayList a = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
    a.add(1);
Here, we created a arraylist of object, but adding 1 primitive integer, it&#39;s still valid because it&#39;s get converted into the Integer wrapper and Object is the superclass of Integer wrapper class. So if you write :

    Object ab = new Object();
    ab=1;
it&#39;s valid. so when you add 1 into the arraylist, your primitive 1 get&#39;s converted into the Integer wrapper class refered by Object class.

I hope this simplifies you.

In Addition with your comment, In the ArrayList class source code, you can see the array which stores all the element is nothing but:

     /**
         * The array buffer into which the elements of the ArrayList are stored.
         * The capacity of the ArrayList is the length of this array buffer. Any
         * empty ArrayList with elementData == DEFAULTCAPACITY_EMPTY_ELEMENTDATA
         * will be expanded to DEFAULT_CAPACITY when the first element is added.
         */
        transient Object[] elementData; // non-private to simplify nested class access

It&#39;s a Object class&#39;s array. So it can store any object and since, the ArrayList class implement the generics, it&#39;s easy to convert this object to the specific type, if the ArrayList is created with specific one.

